11:14.467 --> 11:16.267
I know.
I'm really flattered.

11:16.333 --> 11:18.067
I have to organize
the memorial for him,

11:18.133 --> 11:20.400
so that's gonna be a bit--
but, you know, still.

11:20.467 --> 11:23.067
Right on.
Uh, is it good money?

11:23.133 --> 11:25.000
Yeah, yeah. It's great
in teacher money.

11:25.067 --> 11:26.167
In real money, no, it's shit.

11:26.233 --> 11:27.633
But isn't that inspiring?

11:27.700 --> 11:30.867
I just started back, and my
career's basically on fire.

11:30.933 --> 11:32.100
Couple of years from now,

11:32.167 --> 11:34.300
I could be Secretary
of Education.

11:34.367 --> 11:36.700
- How was your interview?
- Oh, it sucked.

11:36.767 --> 11:37.933
My new thing is I sweat,

11:38.000 --> 11:40.600
like rolling cascades
of sweat down my body.

11:40.667 --> 11:42.100
Ugh. Why?

11:42.167 --> 11:44.733
Because the school run
is like a contact sport,

11:44.800 --> 11:46.000
and, you know,
they're so filthy

11:46.067 --> 11:48.400
that after I get home
I have to take a shower.

11:48.467 --> 11:49.767
And then,
after I take a shower,

11:49.833 --> 11:51.467
I sweat for at least
two and a half hours.

11:51.533 --> 11:53.133
You know that.
And, you know,

11:53.200 --> 11:54.700
I don't have a reference
from Braeband,

11:54.767 --> 11:56.033
so that's making me sweat.

11:56.100 --> 11:58.433
Well just-- just try
and relax a little bit.

11:58.500 --> 11:59.600
You know, maybe--
maybe use it

11:59.667 --> 12:01.100
as an opportunity
to make a little joke.

12:01.167 --> 12:02.467
Like make a joke
about their air conditioning:

12:02.533 --> 12:04.933
if they hire you, they could
afford air conditioning.

12:05.000 --> 12:06.333
Yeah, I'll try that.

12:06.400 --> 12:08.500
And you know what?
Fuck Braeband.

12:08.567 --> 12:10.100
Tell them you've been
a stay-at-home dad

12:10.167 --> 12:11.333
for the last three years.

12:11.400 --> 12:12.667
I'd like to see
any of them try that.

12:12.733 --> 12:13.767
You're a hero.

12:13.833 --> 12:16.000
I mean, you're not,
but they don't know that.

12:22.667 --> 12:23.933
For the last three years

12:24.000 --> 12:26.100
I've been fathering
domestically,

12:26.167 --> 12:28.767
uh, which is to say
I've been a stay-at-home dad.

12:28.833 --> 12:30.133
I'm lucky enough
to have a wife

12:30.200 --> 12:32.067
whose career
made that possible.

12:32.133 --> 12:33.867
Oh. What does your wife do?

12:33.933 --> 12:36.167
My wife?

12:36.233 --> 12:40.567
Oh, she uh... you know,
uh, you know on planes?

12:40.633 --> 12:42.367
You know the air vents?

12:42.433 --> 12:46.300
Like, the nozzles that blow
cooling air onto you?

12:46.367 --> 12:49.533
My wife did a redesign
of those and patented it

12:49.600 --> 12:52.833
and sold it to Boeing
and Airbus.

12:52.900 --> 12:55.900
And a Chinese planes company.

12:55.967 --> 12:58.067
You missed a button
on your shirt.

12:58.133 --> 13:01.500
Oh-- [chuckle]
No, I didn't. My, uh--

13:01.567 --> 13:03.533
My son tore it off
this morning.

13:03.600 --> 13:04.800
You have a safety pin?

13:04.867 --> 13:06.533
No.

13:08.567 --> 13:11.300
If you hire me,
you'll do so well,

13:11.367 --> 13:13.100
you could afford
air conditioning.

13:15.300 --> 13:17.400
Oh-- Is-- Is--
You have. Okay.

13:18.500 --> 13:20.233
I'm so hot.

13:21.300 --> 13:22.933
I was wondering
if I should get the kids

13:23.000 --> 13:24.067
to write a little thing

13:24.133 --> 13:26.333
about Mr. Humphries
for the memorial.

13:26.400 --> 13:28.233
That would be moving,
wouldn't it?

13:28.300 --> 13:29.533
I just wrote
a little something,

13:29.600 --> 13:31.133
and I just moved myself.

13:31.200 --> 13:32.433
Well,
people don't really care

13:32.500 --> 13:34.167
when someone in
the corporate world dies.

13:34.233 --> 13:35.900
I mean, I just want
to do something

13:35.967 --> 13:38.100
that isn't just,
you know, the same old--

13:38.167 --> 13:39.600
Like, I want to honor him,

13:39.667 --> 13:40.700
and I want the kids to know

13:40.767 --> 13:42.500
that it's okay to be
messed up by all this

13:42.567 --> 13:44.833
and also-- and this is
third down the list--

13:44.900 --> 13:46.300
but also let them know

13:46.367 --> 13:47.633
there's a new sheriff
in town--

13:49.000 --> 13:50.733
of Upper Juniors.

13:54.233 --> 13:56.100
That book
must be fascinating.

13:56.167 --> 13:57.900
What are you reading?

13:57.967 --> 13:59.633
Pinochet's autobiography.

13:59.700 --> 14:00.733
Christ.

14:00.800 --> 14:03.400
It's not an autobiography.
It's a biography.

14:03.467 --> 14:05.533
What would
his autobiography say?

14:05.600 --> 14:09.233
"I'm amazing. Nothing's wrong.
I'm planting flowers."

14:09.300 --> 14:11.000
[laugh] Yeah, I guess.

14:11.067 --> 14:12.333
What are you reading?

14:12.400 --> 14:14.833
I'm reading
The Sun Also Rises.

14:14.900 --> 14:16.100
It's a proper book.

14:16.167 --> 14:17.600
You've been reading
that since we met.

14:17.667 --> 14:18.967
Are you memorizing it?

14:19.033 --> 14:20.567
Because, you know,

14:20.633 --> 14:22.767
if you're gonna be
Secretary of Education,

14:22.833 --> 14:25.733
you might try reading
more than one book
every four years.

14:25.800 --> 14:27.367
Well, that's mean.

14:27.433 --> 14:30.633
Oh, by the way, I told your
air conditioning joke today,

14:30.700 --> 14:34.133
and I looked like a fucking
idiot, so thanks for that.

14:35.833 --> 14:38.533
Well, you probably
told it wrong.

14:38.600 --> 14:40.433
Dan: You don't tell
an interviewer

14:40.500 --> 14:41.967
you're a stay-at-home dad.

14:42.033 --> 14:43.267
I mean, that's fine to say

14:43.333 --> 14:45.500
at a garden party
or in Sweden,

14:45.567 --> 14:47.800
but-- but--
but not here, okay?

14:47.867 --> 14:49.767
- Okay, but, uh--
- Yeah, over here,

14:49.833 --> 14:51.333
men work in real jobs,
do you understand that?

14:51.400 --> 14:52.767
Uh, hang on a second.

14:52.833 --> 14:56.133
Uh, so I spoke to Frankie,
and he said he didn't do it,

14:56.200 --> 14:59.233
so, you know, I think
it might be a case
of, you know--

14:59.300 --> 15:01.133
That is the world that we're
trying to get you a job in.

15:01.200 --> 15:02.267
I'm sorry. I don't think
it's good enough

15:02.333 --> 15:03.400
just to say he didn't do it.

15:03.467 --> 15:04.900
Can I just
finish this call?

15:04.967 --> 15:06.833
Wolf's lost a lot
of confidence over--

15:06.900 --> 15:08.167
All right, first interviews

15:08.233 --> 15:10.200
are about "Can I work
with you? Are you a prick?"

15:10.267 --> 15:11.300
He wet the bed last night

15:11.367 --> 15:12.900
for the first time
since last week.

15:12.967 --> 15:14.567
Uh, look, I'd like
to settle this--

15:14.633 --> 15:16.367
And I'd like
for my son to be able

15:16.433 --> 15:18.500
to attend school without
fear of being disfigured.

15:18.567 --> 15:20.867
Is there a piece
of your son missing?

15:20.933 --> 15:22.967
Did my son bite a piece
of flesh out of your son?

15:23.033 --> 15:25.267
- No, but he's--
- I don't have a job
right now, okay?

15:25.333 --> 15:27.100
I am unemployed,
and as a result,

15:27.167 --> 15:28.800
my family might not
have a home soon.

15:28.867 --> 15:30.267
Okay?
So I have priorities.

15:30.333 --> 15:31.600
Well,
my son is my priority.

15:31.667 --> 15:33.600
Just tell me
what you want me to do.

15:33.667 --> 15:35.633
Do you want to bite my son?
Would that help?

15:35.700 --> 15:37.067
Do you want me to bite him?

15:37.133 --> 15:38.867
Hey, Woof.

15:38.933 --> 15:41.000
You wanna bite Frankie?

15:41.067 --> 15:43.000
Just tell me
what you want me to do.

15:44.133 --> 15:45.433
- Rob?
- What?

15:45.500 --> 15:47.267
We just got
an interview for you

15:47.333 --> 15:49.500
at Harbury Capital.
They'd like to see you
this afternoon.

15:49.567 --> 15:52.400
Wow. Really?
Well, that's great.

15:52.467 --> 15:54.700
Ha ha.
Well, that's wonderful.

15:54.767 --> 15:56.100
Did you hear that?

15:57.600 --> 16:00.567
Derek Humphries
was a beloved teacher.

16:00.633 --> 16:03.967
He loved music,
and he loved jokes.

16:04.033 --> 16:06.667
He enjoyed having fun.

16:06.733 --> 16:08.267
We all remember the time

16:08.333 --> 16:10.867
he printed permission slips
for the Easter field trip

16:10.933 --> 16:12.933
on the wrong sized paper

16:13.000 --> 16:14.733
and passed them out anyway.

16:14.800 --> 16:16.767
[student coughs]

16:16.833 --> 16:19.033
Ms. Norris and year 5

16:19.100 --> 16:22.367
have prepared a musical
tribute to his memory.

16:22.433 --> 16:25.567
Ms. Norris, I'll let you
introduce the performance.

16:25.633 --> 16:26.500
[hoarse] Hi--

16:26.567 --> 16:28.900
Oh. [cough]
Sorry, a bit nervous.

16:28.967 --> 16:31.733
[chuckle]
Hi. So, uh, yeah,

16:31.800 --> 16:32.967
so I just wanted to say

16:33.033 --> 16:35.600
that, uh, while we all
loved Mr. Humphries,

16:35.667 --> 16:37.867
I'm sure some of you
are troubled

16:37.933 --> 16:41.567
by the fact that he took
his own, uh, what he did--

16:41.633 --> 16:44.667
Uh, and I don't think
I'd be doing my job

16:44.733 --> 16:46.467
as head of upper juniors

16:46.533 --> 16:50.067
if I didn't say that if any
of you are thinking of...

16:50.133 --> 16:53.433
d-doing something, uh,
like he did,

16:53.500 --> 16:54.533
then, you know,

16:54.600 --> 16:56.100
don't. [chuckle]

16:56.167 --> 16:58.000
Uh, my door is always open.

16:58.067 --> 16:59.300
Um, I mean that.

16:59.367 --> 17:02.500
Um, it's hard--
it's hard being a kid.

17:02.567 --> 17:04.333
I know that. Um,

17:04.400 --> 17:07.067
I've had tough times
in my life

17:07.133 --> 17:12.100
from about 22 to about...
yeah, maybe 34.

17:12.167 --> 17:13.300
I-- I had tough times.

17:13.367 --> 17:14.467
I had acne in adulthood.

17:14.533 --> 17:16.400
Um, a lot of times,
people tell you

17:16.467 --> 17:18.733
you wrap all that up
in your teenage years.

17:18.800 --> 17:21.567
It's not true for everyone.

17:21.633 --> 17:23.833
So, um-- yeah,

17:23.900 --> 17:25.567
year five are gonna
perform a song,

17:25.633 --> 17:29.267
uh, we wrote about
Mr. Humphries, so up.

17:29.333 --> 17:32.033
Uh, they rehearsed very hard,

17:32.100 --> 17:36.333
so if any of you feel like,
you know, dancing or swaying,

17:36.400 --> 17:37.900
then, uh, just go right ahead.

17:37.967 --> 17:39.600
- No dancing.
- Okay.

17:40.833 --> 17:43.967
**

17:44.033 --> 17:45.400
Lets just start again

17:45.467 --> 17:48.800
because Kira, uh--
started ahead of--

17:48.867 --> 17:50.067
Okay.

17:50.133 --> 17:52.567
